<section class="article-body">

  <p>
    I arrived at Rebel Food &amp; Drink immediately after driving through what I can only assume was Edmonton's audition to become Atlantis.
  </p>

  <p>
    The flash flood had people stopping in the middle of the road, throwing on their hazard lights, and collectively deciding that forward progress was no longer their responsibility. Entire intersections had turned into swimming pools. Traffic laws became little more than optimistic suggestions. By the time I arrived, I felt like I deserved a commemorative lifeguard whistle.
  </p>

  <p>
    I was meeting a friend who had also survived the sinking of Edmonton, but she was running late. As the minutes ticked by, I became increasingly convinced the staff had quietly concluded I had been stood up. Honestly, I probably would have reached the same conclusion.
  </p>

  <p>
    While waiting, I asked the bartender what her favorite cocktail to make was. Without hesitation, she said, "The Marilyn Monroe." It consists of Empress 1908 Indigo Gin, Angostura bitters, lemon juice, lime juice, simple syrup, and egg whites. She described it with the confidence of someone introducing me to the greatest cocktail ever conceived.
  </p>

  <p>
    Naturally, I ignored the recommendation and ordered a La Madrina first.
  </p>

  <img
  src="/images/la-madrina.jpg"
  alt="La Madrina cocktail at Rebel Food & Drink"
  class="article-inline-image"
/>

  <p>
    With a completely expressionless face, she informed me that the La Madrina was her least favorite drink to make.
  </p>

  <p>
    For a solid five seconds, I genuinely believed I had become the most inconvenient customer she'd seen all day. Then it clicked. Not a smile. Not a smirk. Nothing. Just elite-level deadpan humor delivered with such conviction that I started wondering if being stood up was somehow also my fault.
  </p>

  <p>
    Once my friend finally navigated her way through what remained of Edmonton, I ordered the Marilyn Monroe.
  </p>

  <p>
    The bartender was absolutely right. It was phenomenal.
  </p>

  <p>
    Both cocktails were exceptional, but what really made the experience memorable was the bartender herself. Her service was attentive, welcoming, and genuinely excellent. Her deadpan delivery was so perfectly committed that every interaction felt like I was one sentence away from becoming the punchline without ever knowing when the joke started. That level of comedic timing deserves its own menu item.
  </p>

  <p>
    I came to Rebel expecting great cocktails and a great visit. Instead, I survived a flash flood, briefly accepted that the staff probably thought I'd been abandoned, unintentionally ordered the bartender's least favorite drink to make, discovered two incredible cocktails, and left wondering if I had been expertly messed with for the better part of an hour.
  </p>

</section>

<section class="final-verdict">

  <h2>Final Verdict</h2>

  <p class="closing-line">
    Five stars without hesitation. I'll absolutely be back. The drinks alone are worth the trip. The bartender's dry, expressionless humor is worth driving through another flood for. I still don't know how many jokes were made at my expense, but I respect the commitment enough to come back and find out.
  </p>

</section>

